      <body>
			<div type="edition" xml:lang="pyx-Latn">
				<ab>
					<lb n="1"/>
					ḅaṁḥ va ḅaṁḥ
					rmaḥ
					tḅaḥ saṁḥ to tḅaṁḥ ta ḅa hi <!-- MM2AG: how should Sastri's possible r- be handled? can I leave the parentheses as is in Blagden? do parentheses in Blagden also mean supplied as in conventions.rtf? -->
					<!-- AG2MM2: this is perennial problem and I don't know what is best practise. Let's agree for the time being that we precisely represent in <rdg> what the source in question has, without interpreting it into our system of editorial conventions. -->
					<!-- AG2MM3: as soon as you reach 007-008, our newly established rule will run into trouble, because in the RTFs I believe I have regularized Blagden/Krech readings to a certain extent. -->
					<!-- MM2AG: I have not added # to Sastri and Blagden, as their quotations come from the same volume of ASB which has a single xml:id. Would it make sense to tag those readings as resp="#Sastri" source="#ASB"? Added #...1985 to Luce to match xml:id in bibliography. -->
				</ab>
			</div>
			<div type="apparatus">
				<listApp>
					<app loc="1">
						<lem>rmaḥ</lem>
						<note>Sastri (ASB 1915, 22) also recognizes the possibility of a prescript <seg type="graphemic">r</seg>. Luce (PPPB I, 75 n.) reads <seg type="graphemic">meḥ</seg>, firming up Blagden’s <seg type="graphemic">m(e)ḥ</seg> (ASB 1915, 21). <!-- MM2AG: changed the page numbers here and in RTF to be more specific: p. 22 for Sastri and p. 21 for Blagden.) -->
						</note>
					</app>
				<app loc="1">
						<lem>ḅaṁḥ</lem>
						<rdg resp="#Blagden" source="bib:ASB1915">baṁḥ</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>ḅaṁḥ</lem>
						<rdg resp="#Blagden" source="bib:ASB1915">baṁḥ</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>rmaḥ</lem>
						<rdg resp="#Sastri" source="bib:ASB1915">rmaḥ</rdg>
						<rdg resp="#Blagden" source="bib:ASB1915">m(e)ḥ</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:Luce1985_01">meḥ</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>tḅaḥ</lem>
						<rdg resp="#Blagden" source="bib:ASB1915">tbaḥ</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>tḅaṁḥ</lem>
						<rdg resp="#Blagden" source="bib:ASB1915">t(b)aḥ</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>ḅa</lem>
						<rdg resp="#Blagden" source="bib:ASB1915">ba</rdg>
					</app></listApp>
			</div>
			<div type="translation" xml:lang="eng">
				<p><!-- english translation here --></p>
			</div>
			<div type="commentary">
				<p>ASB 1915, § 54, p. 21: “Hmawza E” = “the smallest of the Pyu funeral urns as published in Report for 1913”, reading <seg type="graphemic">baṁ: wa baṁ: m(e): tba: saṁ: to t(b)a: ta (ba) hi</seg></p>
				<p>The words <seg type="graphemic">tḅaḥ</seg>, <seg type="graphemic">tḅaṁḥ</seg> and <seg type="graphemic">ḅaṁḥ</seg> give the impression of possibly being morphologically connected.</p>
				<p>The words <seg type="graphemic">ḅa hi</seg> also figure in PYU <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00001">1</ref>.</p>
				<!-- MM2AG: for now changed all <g> to <seg type="graphemic"> except in comments. Where would I use simple <g>? -->
			</div>
			<div type="bibliography">
				<!--Blagden 1913-14: 127 (E). — ASB 1913, 14-5; 1915, 21-3. — PPPB I, 65, 75 n. 24, 127.-->
				<!--[Todo: markup citedRange elements if necessary]-->
				<p>Reported in <bibl><ptr target="bib:ASB"/><citedRange>1913: 14-5</citedRange></bibl>, which includes a reading of the opening akṣaras. <bibl><ptr target="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01"/><citedRange> 127 (E)</citedRange></bibl> takes note of this urn, but focuses his study on the four (PYU <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00003">3</ref>, <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00004">4</ref>, <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00005">5</ref> and <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00006">6</ref>) that share reference to the Vikrama kings. <bibl><ptr target="bib:ASB"/><citedRange>1915: 21-3</citedRange></bibl> provides complete readings and notes by Blagden and Sastri; in most respects, Sastri is not as compatible with our readings as Blagden. Luce, in <bibl><ptr target="bib:Luce1985_01"/><citedRange>I, 65, 75 n. 24, 127</citedRange></bibl>, provides an overview and offers a modified reading. Re-edited here from published photographs.</p>
				<!-- MM: should Sastri and Blagden be tagged here? Example <name xml:id="Blagden">Blagden</name>. -->
				<!--<listBibl type="secondary-bibliography"/>-->
			<listBibl type="primary"><bibl><ptr target="bib:CPI2018_01"/><citedRange unit="item">DHARMA_INSPYU00002</citedRange></bibl></listBibl></div>
